      <p class="apn-s-section-label">Your Current State</p>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">What Your Score Actually Means</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <div id="apn-s-score-context">
        <!-- JS injects contextual paragraph based on scoreParam -->
      </div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        Elite athletes operate with a cortisol-testosterone ratio that stays low during the training week and recovers fully on rest days. Their HRV stays within 5 to 8% of their 7-day rolling baseline. Their perceived exertion at a given output is stable week over week. That is what a 90+ stress score looks like in practice. Not the absence of hard training. The ability to recover from it.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-s-data-callout">
        <p class="stat" id="apn-s-perf-tax-stat">Up to 40%</p>
        <p class="stat-desc">Estimated reduction in anabolic hormone availability when cortisol is chronically elevated above 18 mcg/dL. Testosterone synthesis slows. Growth hormone pulses flatten. The training stimulus remains. The adaptation does not.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tier-conditional framing blocks -->
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie">
        <div class="apn-s-pull-quote">
          <p>"This is the most important single change you will make this month. Your body cannot build muscle, maintain motivation, or sleep deeply while the HPA axis is firing at red. Stress management is not a soft skill. It is the foundation everything else sits on."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-s-body">You are early in building the performance architecture. That means your gains from closing this gap will be the largest of any tier. Every dollar of recovery you invest right now pays at the highest rate.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor">
        <div class="apn-s-pull-quote">
          <p>"One gap is holding back every other area of your training. This is it. Your nutrition, sleep, and training are all running through the same bottleneck: your stress load. Close it first."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-s-body">You have the foundation. Your training is consistent. But your ceiling is compressed by chronic cortisol. The energy, recovery, and motivation you are missing are not a programming problem. They are a stress problem.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete">
        <div class="apn-s-pull-quote">
          <p>"You are in the optimization zone. The gains from here come from precision, not volume. Stress is the last significant drag on your performance ceiling."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-s-body">Your training is dialed. Your nutrition is solid. What separates where you are from where your performance ceiling actually sits is HPA axis management. HRV data tracking starts this week.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite">
        <div class="apn-s-pull-quote">
          <p>"At your level, stress is a precision variable. The margin between a good training block and a great one lives in cortisol management. Most athletes at your level feel this but cannot measure it. You will."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-s-body">Bloodwork and HRV tracking are your tools here. The protocol in Module 4 operates at the specificity your level demands. Nothing generic. Nothing soft.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion">
        <div class="apn-s-pull-quote">
          <p>"Protect this. Your stress management architecture is what sustains peak output across a full season. If cortisol elevation becomes chronic, the cascade touches every other pillar within 3 to 4 weeks."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-s-body">Maintenance is the discipline at this level. Not adding. Not changing what works. Protecting the systems that produced the results you have earned.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#F4F4F2;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Quick Win: Do This Today</p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0 0 12px;"><strong>4-7-8 Box Breathing. Right now. Before you continue reading.</strong></p>
        <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Inhale for 4 counts. Hold for 7. Exhale for 8. Repeat 4 cycles. This activates the parasympathetic branch of the autonomic nervous system via the vagus nerve, directly suppressing cortisol output within minutes. Set a reminder to do this again tonight at 9pm, 30 minutes before bed. That timing matters: evening cortisol suppression is when sleep onset and growth hormone release are most affected.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ====================================================
       MODULE 2: WHY THIS IS COSTING YOU
  ===================================================== -->
  <div id="apn-s-m2" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-s-content">
      <p class="apn-s-section-label">The Science</p>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">The Mechanism Behind Your Gap</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        The hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis, the HPA axis, is your body's central stress response system. When a stressor registers, the hypothalamus releases corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH). That triggers ACTH from the pituitary. ACTH signals the adrenal glands to release cortisol. Under normal acute stress, this system fires, resolves, and returns to baseline. Under chronic stress, it does not return to baseline. It stays elevated.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        Chronically elevated cortisol suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis. This directly reduces luteinizing hormone (LH) output, which is the signal your testes require to produce testosterone. At the same time, elevated cortisol blunts pulsatile growth hormone release from the anterior pituitary. You train hard. The anabolic hormones required to rebuild from that training are suppressed. The stimulus is there. The adaptation is not.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        There is also the allostatic load problem. Your body does not distinguish between training stress and life stress. They draw from the same recovery budget. A 90-minute hard training session and a high-stakes workday both elevate cortisol through the same HPA axis pathway. Two hard sessions in a week plus work stress is not two sources of stress. It is one pool that is being drained faster than it is filling.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-s-data-callout">
        <p class="stat">27%</p>
        <p class="stat-desc">Reduction in serum cortisol levels measured in a double-blind, placebo-controlled trial of KSM-66 Ashwagandha at 600mg daily over 8 weeks. The same trial recorded a 17% increase in testosterone in the intervention group. This is not a secondary effect. The cortisol reduction directly disinhibits the HPG axis.</p>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        Cortisol is also directly catabolic to muscle tissue. Elevated cortisol accelerates muscle protein breakdown via ubiquitin-proteasome pathway activation. This means you can be in a caloric surplus, hitting protein targets, and still be in a net catabolic state if cortisol remains chronically elevated. The breakdown rate exceeds the synthesis rate.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:22px;color:#0D0D0D;margin:40px 0 12px;">How This Degrades Your Other Pillars</h3>

      <p class="apn-s-body">
        <strong>Sleep:</strong> Elevated evening cortisol delays sleep onset and suppresses slow-wave sleep. SWS is when 80% of daily growth hormone is released. Stress degrades sleep. Poor sleep elevates cortisol the next morning. The feedback loop tightens until HRV trends down for weeks.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-s-body">
        <strong>Nutrition:</strong> Chronic cortisol drives preferential fat storage in visceral tissue and increases cravings for high-sugar, high-fat foods via dopamine system activation. Your appetite and body composition response to food shifts when cortisol is elevated.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-s-body">
        <strong>Training output:</strong> A high cortisol-to-testosterone ratio is the primary hormonal marker of overtraining. Most athletes experience this as flat training sessions, stalled strength numbers, and reduced motivation. They respond by training harder. This compounds the problem.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-s-warning">
        <p class="apn-s-warning-label">Common Mistake</p>
        <p>Training through a high-stress period without adjusting volume. When life stress is elevated, total recovery capacity is reduced. Maintaining full training volume while under significant life stress creates the same HPA axis burden as overtraining. The correct response is to reduce training volume by 20 to 30% during high-stress periods, not to push harder to "counteract" the stress.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tier-conditional cost blocks -->
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">At the Rookie tier, chronic stress is suppressing the anabolic response you need to build your base. You are putting in the training stimulus but your body is rebuilding at 60 to 70% of its potential because the hormonal environment is catabolic. The gains you are working for are being partially erased between sessions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">At the Competitor tier, you have enough base fitness that you can train despite chronic stress. That is the danger. You feel functional but your hormonal profile is suppressed. Testosterone may be 15 to 25% below your baseline. Growth hormone pulses are blunted. Your training ceiling is compressed without a clear external signal of why.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">At the Athlete tier, this shows up as a performance ceiling you cannot breach. You train consistently. You recover reasonably well. But the month-over-month strength and conditioning gains have slowed or stalled. That plateau is often a cortisol-testosterone ratio problem, not a programming problem. HRV data will confirm this.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">At the Elite tier, a 10% cortisol elevation above your personal baseline represents a meaningful suppression of anabolic output. The difference between a sub-optimal training block and a peak performance block lives in these precision margins. Bloodwork measuring free testosterone and morning cortisol will quantify exactly what you are leaving on the table.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">At the Champion tier, stress management is a longevity variable. A single high-stress quarter, unmanaged, can compress a season of gains. The HPA axis dysregulation compounds. It does not self-correct without deliberate intervention. Protect the hormonal environment you have built.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

