  <!-- ====================================================
       MODULE 4: THE PROTOCOL
  ===================================================== -->
  <div id="apn-s-m4" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-s-content">
      <p class="apn-s-section-label">The Protocol</p>
      <h2 class="apn-s-headline">Your 30-Day Stress Closure Plan</h2>
      <div class="apn-s-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Four weeks. One gap. Here is exactly what to do. Each week builds on the previous. Do not skip ahead. The architecture matters as much as the individual actions.</p>

      <!-- WEEK 1 -->
      <p class="apn-s-week-header">Week 1</p>
      <h3 class="apn-s-week-title">Establish Your Baseline: HRV and Parasympathetic Activation</h3>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Before you can manage stress, you need to measure it. HRV (heart rate variability) is the most reliable non-invasive proxy for HPA axis load and autonomic nervous system balance. High HRV indicates parasympathetic dominance and good recovery capacity. Low or declining HRV means your sympathetic nervous system is running hot.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 1: Start HRV tracking daily.</strong> Take your HRV reading every morning before getting out of bed, within 5 minutes of waking. Use Elite HRV, Whoop, or the Apple Health app. Record it in a note. 7 days of data gives you a reliable baseline. Do not make training decisions from a single reading.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 2: One deliberate parasympathetic session daily.</strong> Choose ONE of the following: 5 minutes of box breathing (4 seconds in, 4 hold, 4 out, 4 hold), a 15 to 20 minute walk outside with no earphones, or 2 to 3 minutes of cold water exposure (shower or submersion). Each of these activates vagal tone, which directly downregulates cortisol output via the cholinergic anti-inflammatory pathway. Do this at the same time each day, ideally in the evening when cortisol naturally declines.</p>

      <!-- Tier block for Week 1 -->
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">One action only: the 5-minute box breathing session every evening at 9pm. Download an HRV app and take one reading tomorrow morning. That is it. Nothing else added this week. Lock these two habits before continuing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">HRV daily plus one parasympathetic session. Additionally, for this week, cap your hardest training sessions at 75% of your normal perceived exertion. You are establishing a stress baseline, not adding to the load. Accurate data requires a stabilization window.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">HRV daily. Three different parasympathetic modalities this week (box breathing, cold exposure, and a walk) to identify which produces the largest HRV response for you. That one becomes your daily protocol going forward. Log all three responses.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">HRV daily. If available, request morning cortisol and free testosterone bloodwork this week to establish a hard baseline. The HRV data and bloodwork together give you a complete picture of where your cortisol-testosterone ratio sits right now. Target morning cortisol under 15 mcg/dL and free testosterone above 100 pg/mL as your performance benchmarks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Audit your current parasympathetic protocols. Are they consistent? Scheduled? Or reactive? This week is about systematizing what you may already be doing informally. Every recovery intervention gets scheduled. Nothing informal at this tier.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-s-assignment">
        <p class="apn-s-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>By end of Week 1: 7 consecutive days of morning HRV readings recorded. At least 5 of 7 daily parasympathetic sessions completed. Note your average HRV and your average resting heart rate. These are your Week 1 baseline numbers. You will measure against them on Day 30.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 2 -->
      <p class="apn-s-week-header" style="margin-top:48px;">Week 2</p>
      <h3 class="apn-s-week-title">Supplement Stack and Training Load Calibration</h3>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Week 2 introduces your cortisol management supplement stack (covered in full in Module 5) and begins using HRV data to make real training decisions. This is where the protocol becomes measurable.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 1: Training load adjusted to HRV.</strong> Establish a simple rule now: if your morning HRV is more than 8% below your 7-day rolling average, that day is a recovery or low-intensity session. No exceptions. Pushing through a low-HRV day adds cortisol to a system that is already running hot. The training stress goes in. The adaptation does not come out.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 2: Identify your highest-stress time window each day.</strong> This is usually mid-afternoon for most working athletes. Schedule your parasympathetic session to occur immediately before or immediately after this window. Cortisol spikes predictably. You are placing your intervention where the spike is largest.</p>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Add the supplement protocol from Module 5. Use HRV only as a green-light check. If HRV is down significantly, reduce your training session to a 20-minute walk plus mobility work. Do not skip the workout entirely. Reduced intensity keeps the habit intact while lowering the cortisol cost.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Implement the HRV rule strictly. Add the supplement stack. Begin mapping which days of the week your HRV is typically lowest. That pattern usually correlates with life stress cycles, not training. Knowing the pattern lets you pre-position parasympathetic sessions before the low-HRV days arrive.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Full supplement stack. HRV rule implemented. Add a training readiness score (1 to 10) each morning next to your HRV reading. After 7 days, look at the correlation. If your subjective readiness and HRV diverge significantly, your stress perception is masked. That is important information.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Full precision stack. HRV rule implemented with a tighter threshold (6% below rolling average). Begin categorizing your training sessions into three load tiers: high, moderate, and recovery. Your weekly schedule should have no more than 2 to 3 high-load sessions, regardless of how good your HRV looks on a given day.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Validate your current supplement timing against the precision protocol in Module 5. Small timing adjustments at your level produce measurable HRV changes within 7 to 10 days. This week is about dialing, not adding.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-s-assignment">
        <p class="apn-s-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>By end of Week 2: Supplement stack started and consistent. At least one HRV-guided training modification made this week. You know your average HRV on high-life-stress days versus low-life-stress days. Write down that number spread.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 3 -->
      <p class="apn-s-week-header" style="margin-top:48px;">Week 3</p>
      <h3 class="apn-s-week-title">Sleep Schedule Becomes Non-Negotiable</h3>

      <p class="apn-s-body">The stress-sleep feedback loop is bidirectional. Cortisol suppresses slow-wave sleep. Poor sleep elevates next-day cortisol by 15 to 25%. You cannot close the stress gap while keeping a variable sleep schedule. This week you lock the sleep anchor.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 1: Fixed wake time, 7 days a week.</strong> Choose a wake time and do not deviate by more than 30 minutes in either direction, including weekends. Your circadian rhythm is set by light exposure and wake time. A consistent wake time stabilizes the cortisol awakening response (CAR), which is the natural cortisol spike in the first 30 to 45 minutes after waking. An irregular wake time produces an irregular CAR, which means your cortisol curve is off for the entire day.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 2: Hard cutoff on artificial light at 9pm.</strong> Blue-light wavelengths suppress melatonin onset by 1 to 3 hours. Delayed melatonin means elevated evening cortisol cannot drop as fast as it needs to for proper sleep onset. Phone to night shift mode or off. No screens after 9pm is the target. If unavoidable, blue-light blocking glasses are an acceptable intervention.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 3: Last meal at least 2.5 hours before bed.</strong> Insulin elevation from digestion blunts growth hormone release in the first sleep cycle. This amplifies the cortisol effect on GH suppression. Eating closer to bed compounds the hormonal problem your stress gap is already creating.</p>

      <!-- Scripture block - placed naturally mid-protocol -->
      <div class="apn-s-scripture">
        <p>"Do you not know that your bodies are temples of the Holy Spirit, who is in you, whom you have received from God? You are not your own; you were bought at a price. Therefore honor God with your bodies."</p>
        <p>1 Corinthians 6:19-20</p>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Stewardship of the body is not optional. Sleep is not weakness. Recovery is not laziness. They are the obedient management of what you have been given to work with. The protocol demands rest because the physiology demands rest. Both are true at the same time.</p>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">One thing: consistent wake time. Set the alarm for the same time every day this week. That is the only new variable. The light cutoff and meal timing can be added in Week 4. One anchor at a time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Consistent wake time plus 9pm light cutoff. Two variables. Track how long it takes you to fall asleep each night (approximate is fine). If sleep onset is still over 20 minutes with these changes, your evening cortisol is still elevated. This will be addressed by the supplement timing in Module 5.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">All three sleep anchors implemented simultaneously. Log subjective sleep quality each morning on a 1 to 10 scale. Compare Week 3 average to Week 1 average. A meaningful improvement here will be confirmed by HRV trending upward. Look for both signals.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Sleep environment precision: bedroom temperature 65 to 68 degrees Fahrenheit. Blackout curtains. No phone in the room. Your sleep architecture at the Elite tier is a tool as deliberate as your training programming. Treat it accordingly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">If your sleep schedule is already consistent, this week is about protecting it. Identify the highest-risk threat to your sleep schedule (social events, late work sessions) and create a pre-commitment rule for each. The schedule does not bend.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-s-assignment">
        <p class="apn-s-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>By end of Week 3: Wake time identical all 7 days (within 30 minutes). 9pm light cutoff achieved at least 5 of 7 nights. Record your subjective sleep quality average for the week. Compare to Week 1 baseline. Note any change in morning HRV trend.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 4 -->
      <p class="apn-s-week-header" style="margin-top:48px;">Week 4</p>
      <h3 class="apn-s-week-title">Review, Optimize, and Measure Day 30</h3>

      <p class="apn-s-body">Week 4 is about measuring the gap you have closed and optimizing the stack based on your real response data. You have 21 days of HRV data and subjective logs. Use them.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 1: HRV trend review.</strong> Compare your average HRV from Week 4 to your Week 1 baseline. A consistent 5 to 10% increase in HRV average indicates improved parasympathetic tone and reduced allostatic load. If HRV has not moved, the bottleneck is either supplement consistency, sleep schedule compliance, or a life stress variable you have not addressed. Identify which one.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 2: Stack optimization.</strong> Review your supplement compliance from Weeks 2 and 3. If you missed doses on certain days, identify the pattern and solve the logistics (better placement, phone reminder, linking to an existing habit). If you have been consistent, evaluate whether you are ready to add the next tier product from Module 5 based on your tier.</p>

      <p class="apn-s-body"><strong>Action 3: Measure performance output.</strong> Pick one measurable training metric from Week 1 (a lift number, a conditioning benchmark, a resting heart rate) and test it again this week. The protocol's job is to move performance numbers. If this gap is closing, you will see it in the data.</p>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Write down your Day 30 numbers: average HRV, resting heart rate, and one subjective score (energy on a scale of 1 to 10, averaged over the week). Compare to Day 1. The gap between those two measurements is what you closed. That is real. Build on it in Month 2.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">HRV review plus a training performance comparison. If numbers are up and HRV is up, the protocol is working. Your next step is sustaining it and retaking the quiz in 30 more days to confirm the score movement. Do not abandon what is working because you feel better.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Full data review: HRV trend, subjective sleep quality trend, training performance metric, supplement compliance rate. Identify the one variable with the weakest performance. That is your Month 2 focus. The other variables can hold at their current level.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">If you had baseline bloodwork from Week 1, retest morning cortisol and free testosterone. HRV data provides the directional signal. Bloodwork confirms the hormonal mechanism. If free testosterone has moved 10 to 15% from baseline, the HPA axis suppression has been measurably reduced. That is the target.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-s-body" style="margin:0;">Architecture review. Which protocols are now automatic? Which still require deliberate effort? The ones that require effort are still fragile. Systematize them further. The ones that are automatic are your foundation. Protect them heading into Month 2.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-s-assignment">
        <p class="apn-s-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>Day 30 measurements: Average HRV (Week 4 vs. Week 1). Resting heart rate. One training performance marker. Supplement compliance rate (percentage of days taken as prescribed). Write all four numbers down. Retake the Performance Quiz at the link in Module 7 and compare your stress pillar score to your starting score.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

